This bed has a beaten straw mattress, lined with well worn cotton sheets and covered with a worn woolen blanket.  Tended quite well, washed and scented, you will not find any bedbugs living here.  Soft enough to allow even the most hard adventurer a decent nights rest.

Garlic is well known as a herb for flavoring foods and treating heat stroke among the preasantry. It is also used to repulse vampires.

Named after a wizard from Neverwinter, haunspeir is sold as a tobacco-like paste or dried in a pill form. It is used by wizards and others who need to rapidly boast their intelligence.

Type: Ingested DC12
Initial Effect: 1d4 points of damage
Secondary Effect: 1d4 + 1 bonus to Intelligence for 1d10 + 15 minutes.
Side Effects: All slashing and peircing damage against the target gains an extra point.
Overdose: If more than 1 is taken within 24 hours, the target suffers an immediate 2d4 points of damage (no save)
Addiction: Low

This book describes the material components needed to cast certain Arcane spells. Components marked with {f} are not consumed in the casting most of the time. Occasionally, the power of the spell destroys the focus component. The chance of this increases with the difficulty of the spell. The term "plus" is used to separate two distinct components.
